{{Political anthropology}}
'''Lesley Gill''' is an author and a professor of [[anthropology]] at [[Vanderbilt University]].  Her research focusses on [[political violence]], gender, free market reforms and human rights in [[Latin America]], especially [[Bolivia]].<ref name=prospect>{{cite news|url=http://www.prospect.org/cs/articles?article=the_miseducation_of_latin_america|title=The Miseducation of Latin America|last=Mandel|first=Aaron|date=15 December 2004|work=Prospect|accessdate=22 December 2010}}</ref>  She also writes about the military training that takes place at the [[Western Hemisphere Institute for Security Cooperation|School of the Americas]]<ref name=prospect/> and has campaigned for its closure.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1203774,00.html|title=Targeting a "School for Strongmen"|last=Friedman-Rudovsky|first=Jean|date=13 June 2006|work=Time Magazine|accessdate=22 December 2010}}</ref> She has campaigned with [[Witness for Peace]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.american.edu/cas/connections/upload/october_2002.pdf|title=Department News|date=October 2002|work=CAS Connections|publisher=American University|accessdate=22 December 2010}}</ref>

==Education and work==
Gill has a B.A. from [[Macalester College]] (1977), and an M.A. (1978), M.Phil. (1980) and Ph.D. (1984) from [[Columbia University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanderbilt.edu/cas/overview/aboutcas/index.php|title=New Tenured/Tenure-track Faculty for the 2008-2009 academic year|work=College of Arts and Science, Vanderbilt University|accessdate=22 December 2010}}</ref> She was a visiting fellow at the [[University of East Anglia]] from 1984 to 1985.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gill|first=Lesley|title=Peasants, entrepreneurs, and social change: frontier development in lowland Bolivia|year=1987|publisher=Westview Press|chapter=Introduction}}</ref> Formerly at the [[American University]] in Washington, she moved in 2008 to Vanderbilt to chair the Department of Anthropology.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sitemason.vanderbilt.edu/vanderbiltview/articles/2008/09/30/new-faculty-lesley-gill.65308|title=New anthropology chair examines political violence in Latin America|last=Salisbury|first=David F.|date=30 September 2008|work=Vanderbilt View|accessdate=22 December 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927020524/http://sitemason.vanderbilt.edu/vanderbiltview/articles/2008/09/30/new-faculty-lesley-gill.65308|archivedate=27 September 2011|df=}}</ref> She is a member of the editorial committee of ''[[Dialectical Anthropology]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.springer.com/social+sciences/archaeology+%26+anthropology/journal/10624?detailsPage=editorialBoard|title=Dialectical Anthropology|publisher=Springer|accessdate=22 December 2010}}</ref>

===Works===
*''Peasants, Entrepreneurs, and Social Change: Frontier Development in Lowland Bolivia'', Westview Press, 1987 {{ISBN|0-8133-7339-5}}
*''Precarious Dependencies: Gender, Class, and Domestic Service in Bolivia'', Columbia University Press, 1994 {{ISBN|0-231-09647-X}}
*''Teetering on the Rim: Global Restructuring, Daily Life, and the Armed Retreat of the Bolivian State'', Columbia University Press, 2000 {{ISBN|0-231-11805-8}}
*''[http://www.dukeupress.edu/Catalog/ViewProduct.php?productid=11773 The School of the Americas: Military Training and Political Violence in the Americas]'', Duke University Press, 2004 {{ISBN|0-8223-3392-9}}

