'''Mihail Jora''' ({{IPA-ro|mihaˈil ˈʒora}}; 2 August 1891, [[Roman, Romania]] - 10 May 1971, [[Bucharest, Romania]]) was a [[Romanian people|Romanian]] composer, pianist, and conductor.<ref Name="Sadie">{{cite book
|title=Calling on the composer: a guide to European composer houses and museums
|last=Sadie
|author2=Julie Anne Sadie |author3=Stanley Sadie
 |year=2005
|publisher=Yale University Press
|location=
|isbn=0-300-10750-1
|page=214
|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KqpRjvynUpQC&pg=PA214&dq=%22Mihail+Jora%22&hl=en&ei=IP3jTIzDHsaqlAfO3pWFDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CDUQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=%22Mihail%20Jora%22&f=false }}</ref>
Jora studied in [[Leipzig]] with [[Robert Teichmüller]]. From 1929 to 1962 he was a professor at the conservatoire of [[Bucharest]]. He worked 1928 to 1933 as a director/conductor of the Broadcasting Orchestra in [[Bucharest]]. In 1944 he became vice-president of the society of Romanian composers: however, he soon came under the reproach of formalism into criticism of the new communist government. In 1953, he was rehabilitated and reallowed to join the Composers' Union.{{Clarify|date=September 2010}}

He composed six [[ballet]]s, one [[symphony]], two major [[orchestra]] works, [[chamber-music]]al works, and many pieces of piano, [[choir]] music, and [[vocal music]].

